<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n16036k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n16" href="#n16036k">N16 (VI.D.1)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n16all.htm#n16036k"> 36(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> putti-cherub</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">There is not room here to trace fully the strange progress from the hermaphroditic archaisms, through the somewhat too animal athleticism of Polycleitos to the Farnese Hercules. As art goes toward Rome, the age of beauty is advanced. Greece itself showed progressive signs of infantilism, turning from the intermediate sex to sexless youth, and finally to an inane exuberance of prize babies, the first froth of <mark>putti-cherub</mark> senile sentiment. The work of this amazing people at the height of their power reveals an obsession with the idea of youth which is already morbid. <small> D. Heard, <a name="HEARD" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#HEARD"><cite title="source">Narcissus, an Anatomy of Clothes</cite></a> (1924) 61</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c02158l" href="c02all.htm#c02158l">VI.C.02:158(l)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
